        "full_description": "Ekadashi, 4 December 2026\n\nThe glory of Utpanna Ekadashi is described in the Bhavishyottara Purana in a conversation between Sri Krishna and Arjuna.\n\nSri Suta Goswami told the assembled brahmanas and sages: \"One who hears with faith and devotion about the glory of Ekadashi and the rules given by Lord Krishna attains happiness in this life and, in the next life, reaches the abode of Lord Vishnu.\"\n\nArjuna once asked Sri Krishna: \"O Janardana, please explain the merit of fasting completely, eating only in the evening, or taking food once at midday on Ekadashi.\"\n\nLord Sri Krishna replied: \"O Arjuna, at the beginning of autumn, on the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in November-December, one should begin the observance of Ekadashi. Early in the morning one should take a vow to fast. At midday one should purify oneself by bathing, praying to Mother Earth to remove the reactions of sinful actions and to grant the path to the supreme abode. After bathing, one should worship Lord Govinda.\"\n\nThe Lord then described how Indra, surrounded by the devas, once approached the Supreme Lord in distress. The devas had been driven from heaven by the powerful demon Mura. Indra prayed: \"O Lord of the universe, O Supreme Personality of Godhead, You are the shelter, mother, and father of all. You create, maintain, and withdraw everything. We have lost our heavenly kingdom and have fallen into suffering. Please be pleased with us.\"\n\nHearing this plea, Lord Vishnu asked Indra to explain who had conquered the devas. Indra answered that the fierce demon Mura, son of Nadijangha, had taken the heavenly kingdom and assumed the positions of the devas. Even when united, the devas could not defeat him.\n\nLord Vishnu became angry on behalf of the devas and went with them to Mura's capital, Chandravati. A terrible battle began. Although the Lord easily defeated the demonic armies, Mura himself could not be subdued by any weapon. The struggle continued for a very long time, and at last the Lord went to Badarikashram and entered a beautiful cave named Hemavati to rest.\n\nMura followed Him into the cave and, seeing the Lord apparently asleep, prepared to attack Him. At that moment a radiant goddess appeared from the Lord's own body, armed with divine weapons. She fought with Mura and cut off his head, causing his followers to flee in fear.\n\nWhen the Lord awoke, He saw Mura lying dead and the effulgent goddess standing before Him with folded palms. He asked who she was. She replied: \"O my Lord, I appeared from Your body and killed this demon. Seeing You asleep, he tried to attack You, and I stopped him.\"\n\nThe Supreme Lord said: \"O Goddess, I am pleased with you and grateful to you. Ask any boon. You are My spiritual energy. Because you appeared on the day of Ekadashi, your name shall be Ekadashi. Whoever observes the vow of Ekadashi will be freed from the reactions of sinful actions and will attain divine happiness.\"\n\nFrom that time onward, Ekadashi has been honored in this world. The Lord told Arjuna that one who follows the Ekadashi vow is awarded the highest destination. He also explained that Ekadashi joined with Dvadashi is especially auspicious, and that on Ekadashi one should avoid sense indulgence, grains and beans, honey, meat, inappropriate vessels, and the use of oil.\n\nThus ends the account of the glory of Utpanna Ekadashi."
