        "description": "Benefits: Grants victory over enemies, helps overcome obstacles, and brings success. Story: Lord Ramachandra observed this fast before marching to Lanka to defeat Ravana.",
        "benefits": "Grants victory over enemies, helps overcome obstacles, and brings success.",
        "story": "Lord Ramachandra observed this fast before marching to Lanka to defeat Ravana.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, February 13, 2026\n\nThe glories of this Ekadashi are described in the Skanda Purana. Once Maharaja Yudhishthira addressed Lord Krishna: “O Lord Krishna, please be kind to me and describe the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of February/March.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O King Yudhishthira! I shall gladly tell you about the Ekadashi known as Vijaya Ekadashi. By observing this Ekadashi, the reactions to sinful activities are immediately destroyed.\n\nOnce the great sage Narada approached Lord Brahma: ‘O best of the demigods! Please tell me about the fruits attained by observing the vow of Vijaya Ekadashi, which falls during the waning moon in the month of February/March.’ Lord Brahma replied: ‘My dear son, this ancient vow is pure and destroys the consequences of all sins. Its fruits are great, as indicated by the very name of this Ekadashi. Without doubt, Vijaya Ekadashi empowers a person to attain victory.\n\nWhen Sri Ramachandra, His consort Sitadevi, and His brother Lakshmana went into exile for fourteen years by the order of Ramachandra’s father, they lived for some time in the beautiful forest known as Panchavati, situated on the bank of the Godavari River. The austere Sitadevi was abducted by Ravana, the king of the demons. Separation from Sita plunged Ramachandra into an ocean of sorrow.\n\nWhile wandering through the forest in search of Sita, Ramachandra encountered Jatayu, the king of birds, who was near death. Jatayu told Ramachandra everything he knew about Sita and then departed from this world and returned to Vaikuntha. Later Ramachandra formed a friendship with Sugriva. Desiring to assist Ramachandra’s mission, numerous monkey soldiers assembled into an army. At that time Hanuman, the king of the monkeys, reached the Ashoka grove in Lanka, where he met Sitadevi and gave her Ramachandra’s ring. Then Hanuman returned to Ramachandra and brought him the news.\n\nAfter hearing Hanuman’s account, Ramachandra met with His friend Sugriva and resolved to invade Lanka. Ramachandra assembled a vast number of monkey soldiers and reached the shore of the ocean. He asked Lakshmana: ‘O Saumitra! How shall we cross this bottomless ocean, teeming with whales and crocodiles?’ Lakshmana replied: ‘O original Supreme Personality of Godhead! You are the original Lord. On this island lives a great sage named Bakadalbhya. His ashrama is four miles from here. O son of the Raghu dynasty! This sage has had the darshan of Lord Brahma. We should ask him how the ocean may be crossed.’\n\nThus, following Lakshmana’s advice, Lord Ramachandra went to the ashrama of Bakadalbhya and offered him respectful obeisances. The omniscient sage immediately understood that the Supreme Personality of Godhead, Ramachandra, stood before him. He had appeared in this material world to kill the demon Ravana. The great sage asked: ‘O Ramachandra, for what purpose have You come here?’ Ramachandra replied: ‘O brahmana! By your mercy I have come here to the shore of the ocean with My soldiers. I desire to fight the demons and conquer Lanka. O best of sages! Please tell Me a simple means by which I can cross the ocean. Only for this reason have I come to your lotus feet.’ The great sage said to Ramachandra: ‘O Ramachandra! I shall tell You about the observance of a great vow by which You will be able to win the battle and obtain fame and prosperity in this world. You must follow this vow with the utmost attention. O Rama! There is an Ekadashi known as Vijaya, which falls in the month of February/March. By observing this Ekadashi, You will be able to cross the ocean together with Your monkey soldiers. O Lord Ramachandra! Now please hear the procedure for observing this Ekadashi.\n\nOn the day before Ekadashi, You should fill a golden, silver, copper, or earthen vessel with water and decorate it with mango shoots. Then this vessel should be placed upon a sanctified elevated altar adorned with seven kinds of grain. After that, a golden deity of Lord Narayana should be placed upon the vessel. On Ekadashi day, You should bathe early in the morning and worship the deity of Lord Narayana with devotion, offering tulasi leaves, sandalwood paste, flowers, garlands, incense, a ghee lamp, and food. At night You should remain awake. On the day after Ekadashi, after sunrise, You should place the vessel on the bank of a river, pond, or lake and properly worship it. Then You should give the vessel and the deity of Narayana in charity to a brahmana who strictly observes the vow of celibacy. By doing all that has been described above, You will certainly prevail over Your enemies.’\n\nFollowing the instructions of this great sage, Lord Ramachandra demonstrated the ideal example of observing this Ekadashi vow and won the battle. A person who properly observes this Ekadashi vow will certainly become victorious both in this life and in the next.\n\nLord Brahma continued, addressing Narada: ‘O my dear son! Therefore, everyone should observe the vow of this Vijaya Ekadashi. The glories of Vijaya Ekadashi destroy all reactions to sinful activities. A person who reads or hears the glories of this Ekadashi obtains the results of the Vajapeya sacrifice.’”"
