      "en": {
        "name": "Papamochani Ekadashi",
        "description": "Benefits: Destroys the reactions of even very grave sins committed in ignorance. Story: Grants forgiveness and helps restore spiritual purity after falldowns.",
        "benefits": "Destroys the reactions of even very grave sins committed in ignorance.",
        "story": "Grants forgiveness and helps restore spiritual purity after falldowns.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, March 15, 2026\n\nThe glories of Papamochani Ekadashi are described in the Bhavishyottara Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nOnce Maharaja Yudhishthira addressed Lord Krishna: “My dear Lord Krishna, You have already told me the glories of Amalaki Ekadashi; now, please tell me about the Ekadashi that occurs during the waning moon in the month of March/April. What is the name of this Ekadashi? What is the process of observing it, and what are its results?”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O best of kings! The name of this Ekadashi is Papamochani. Now please hear of its glories. Long ago, the sage Lomasa narrated the glories of this Ekadashi to King Mandhata.\n\nThis Papamochani Ekadashi falls during the waning moon in the month of March/April. This Ekadashi nullifies all reactions to sinful activities and bestows the eight kinds of mystic perfection.\n\nThe sage Lomasa said: ‘In ancient times, Kubera, the treasurer of the demigods, possessed a beautiful flower-filled forest known as Chaitraratha, where the weather was so pleasant that it seemed eternal spring prevailed.\n\nIn that forest Gandharvas and Kinnaras sported. The demigods, led by Indra, often came to the forest and pleasantly spent their time there. A great sage named Medhavi, a devotee of Lord Shiva, performed austerities in that forest.\n\nThe apsaras—the celestial dancing girls—tried in every way to disturb the sage. Among them was a celebrated apsara named Manju Ghosha. She sought a means to attract the sage’s attention.\n\nFearing the sage, Manju Ghosha built a hut near his ashrama and began singing in her sweet voice while accompanying herself on the vina. Seeing Manju Ghosha, who was anointed with sandalwood paste, adorned with a fragrant flower garland, sweetly singing, and extraordinarily attractive, Cupid, the enemy of Lord Shiva, sought to conquer the sage who worshiped Lord Shiva.\n\nBecause Lord Shiva had burned Cupid to ashes, Cupid, desiring revenge upon his destroyer, entered the body of the sage.\n\nAt that time the sage Medhavi, wearing a white sacred thread upon his body and dwelling in the ashrama of Chyavana Rishi, resembled a second Cupid. Inflamed with lust, Manju Ghosha slowly approached the sage.\n\nThe sage Medhavi also lost his reason because of lust and forgot the Lord whom he worshiped. He abandoned the practice of devotional service and became so intoxicated by the company of the beautiful woman that he lost the ability to distinguish day from night. Thus the sage spent many years in the company of the apsara.\n\nWhen Manju Ghosha finally became convinced that the sage had lost his position, she decided to return to heaven. To Medhavi, who was absorbed in amorous enjoyment, she said: “O great sage! Now please give me permission to return home.”\n\nThe sage replied: “O beautiful woman! You came to me only to stay for the night, but when morning comes you may return.”\n\nHearing these words, Manju Ghosha became afraid and continued living in the sage’s company. Thus, although Manju Ghosha lived with the sage for fifty-seven years, nine months, and three days, to the sage it seemed that only half the night had passed.\n\nThen Manju Ghosha again asked the sage for permission to return home, but the sage said: “O beautiful one! Please listen to me. It is only morning now. Please wait until I finish performing my morning rituals.” Astonished, the apsara smiled and said to the sage: “O great sage! How much time will you need to perform these rituals? Have you still not completed them? You have spent long years enjoying my company. Please consider how precious time is.”\n\nHearing such words from the apsara, the sage came to his senses and, calculating how much time had passed, said: “Alas! O beautiful one! I have wasted fifty-seven precious years of my life. You have caused the ruin of all my ascetic efforts.”\n\nThe sage’s eyes filled with tears, and his whole body trembled. The sage Medhavi cursed Manju Ghosha with these words: “You have behaved toward me like a witch; therefore you shall now become a witch. O sinful woman! Be cursed.”\n\nBeing cursed by the sage, Manju Ghosha humbly said to him: “O best of brahmanas! Please revoke the curse. I spent many years in your company. O my lord, you should forgive me.”\n\nThe sage replied: “O graceful one! What can I do now? You have destroyed all the wealth of my austerities. Nevertheless, I shall tell you of a practice by which you can become free from this curse. The Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of March/April, known as Papamochani, can destroy the consequences of all sinful activities. If you faithfully observe this Ekadashi, your suffering will come to an end.”\n\nHaving said this, the sage Medhavi returned to the ashrama of his spiritual father, the sage Chyavana. Seeing his fallen son, the sage Chyavana became sorrowful and said: “Alas! Alas! O my son, what have you done? You should not have destroyed all the wealth of your austerities by becoming the victim of an ordinary woman.”\n\nThe sage Medhavi replied: “O respected father! I am so unfortunate that I committed great sins in the company of an apsara. Therefore, please instruct me and tell me how I can atone for my sins.”\n\nHearing the plaintive words of his repentant son, the sage Chyavana said: “O my son! By observing Papamochani Ekadashi, which falls during the waning moon in the month of March/April, all reactions to sinful activities are completely destroyed.\n\nTherefore you should observe this Ekadashi.” Having heard these compassionate words from his spiritual father, Medhavi observed this Ekadashi with special enthusiasm.\n\nBy the influence of this Ekadashi, all the reactions to his sinful activities were destroyed, and the sage Medhavi became extraordinarily virtuous.\n\nAt the same time, the beautiful Manju Ghosha also observed this auspicious Papamochani Ekadashi, and by doing so returned to heaven.’\n\nAfter narrating this story to King Mandhata, the sage Lomasa concluded: ‘My dear king, by observing this Ekadashi, all reactions to sinful activities are automatically destroyed. By hearing or reading the glories of this Ekadashi, one attains the results of giving a thousand cows in charity. By observing this Ekadashi, all kinds of sins, such as killing a brahmana, killing an embryo, drinking intoxicants, and committing adultery with the wife of one’s guru, are completely neutralized. Because this sacred Ekadashi is so auspicious and destroys all sins, everyone should observe it.’”"
      }
