      "en": {
        "name": "Varuthini Ekadashi",
        "description": "Benefits: Protects from misfortune, brings auspiciousness, and purifies bad karma. Story: Fasting on this day is praised as giving merit comparable to donating gold.",
        "benefits": "Protects from misfortune, brings auspiciousness, and purifies bad karma.",
        "story": "Fasting on this day is praised as giving merit comparable to donating gold.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, April 13, 2026\n\nThe glories of Varuthini Ekadashi, which falls during the waning moon in the month of April/May, are described in the Bhavishyottara Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nOnce Maharaja Yudhishthira said to Sri Krishna: “O Vasudeva! I offer my humble obeisances unto You. Now, please tell me about the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of April/May. Tell me its name, influence, and glories.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “My dear king, the name of this Ekadashi is Varuthini, and it bestows good fortune upon a person both in this life and in the next. By following this Ekadashi, a living being attains everlasting bliss, destroys the consequences of his sins, and obtains great good fortune. By observing this vow, an unfortunate wife becomes fortunate; a person attains happiness and prosperity both in this life and in the next; people become free from the cycle of birth and death; all the reactions to their sinful activities are nullified; and they attain devotional service to the Lord.\n\nKing Mandhata attained liberation by properly observing this Ekadashi. By observing Varuthini Ekadashi, one can attain the results of performing austerities for ten thousand years. The amount of merit acquired by giving forty kilograms of gold in charity during a solar eclipse at Kurukshetra is obtained simply by observing this Varuthini Ekadashi. O best of kings! It is better to give an elephant in charity than a horse. Better still is to give land, but even better is to give sesame seeds. Giving gold is better than giving sesame seeds, and giving grains is better still. There is no gift superior to grain! O best of kings! By giving grain in charity, one can satisfy the forefathers, the demigods, and all living beings. Learned men have declared that giving a daughter in marriage is equal to giving grain. The Supreme Lord Himself has compared the gift of grain with the gift of cows. Moreover, of all forms of charity, the highest is the distribution of knowledge.\n\nBy observing Varuthini Ekadashi, one can attain the results of all kinds of charity. A person who takes money in exchange for selling his daughter certainly commits a great sin, for which he will remain in hell until the final annihilation of the universe. Therefore, no one should ever accept wealth in exchange for a daughter. O king of kings! A householder who, driven by greed, sells his daughter becomes a cat in his next life. As for a person who decorates his daughter with jewels according to his means and gives her in marriage to a worthy bridegroom, even Chitragupta, the chief secretary of Yamaraja, is unable to calculate the virtue of such a person.\n\nA person observing this Ekadashi should refrain from eating from a metal vessel and should not eat meat, peas, spinach, honey, food cooked by others, or more than once; nor should he engage in sexual relations, beginning from the day before Ekadashi.\n\nOn Ekadashi day, he should not gamble, sleep, chew betel nuts, brush his teeth, criticize anyone, gossip, converse with sinners, become angry, or tell lies.\n\nOn the day after Ekadashi, one should not eat from metal utensils, eat meat, masura gram, or honey; tell lies; exercise; perform heavy labor; eat more than once; engage in sexual relations; shave the head or face; apply oil to the body; or eat food cooked by others.\n\nAll the above should be avoided, otherwise the Ekadashi vow is broken. Along with the restrictions described above, certain prohibitions should be observed not only for these three days but always.\n\nIf a person observes the vow of Varuthini Ekadashi according to the rules and regulations, he becomes free from the reactions to all his sins and attains the supreme goal of life.\n\nOne who remains awake on Ekadashi day and worships Lord Janardana becomes free from all sins and attains the supreme goal of life. Anyone who hears or reads the glories of this Ekadashi obtains the results of giving one thousand cows in charity, becomes free from all sinful reactions, and attains the abode of Vishnu.”"
      }
