      "en": {
        "name": "Mohini Ekadashi",
        "description": "Benefits: Destroys illusion, relieves sorrow, and frees one from material attachments. Story: Connected with the Supreme Lord’s beautiful Mohini form.",
        "benefits": "Destroys illusion, relieves sorrow, and frees one from material attachments.",
        "story": "Connected with the Supreme Lord’s beautiful Mohini form.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, April 27, 2026\n\nThe glories of Mohini Ekadashi, which falls during the waxing moon in the month of April/May, are described in the Surya Purana.\n\nOnce Maharaja Yudhishthira addressed Lord Krishna: “O Janardana! What is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waxing moon in the month of April/May, and what is the process for observing this Ekadashi? What merit does a person acquire by following this Ekadashi? Please tell me about this in detail.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O son of Dharma! Please attentively hear from Me the story that the sage Vasishtha once told Lord Ramachandra. Once Lord Ramachandra asked the great sage Vasishtha: ‘O respected sage! I am experiencing great sorrow caused by separation from Sita, the daughter of King Janaka. Please tell me of a great vow by observing which all reactions to sinful activities and all sorrow disappear.’\n\nThe great sage Vasishtha, Ramachandra’s spiritual master, replied: ‘My dear Rama, Your intelligence is great, and You are endowed with faith. Your question brings benefit to all humanity. Simply by chanting and remembering Your auspicious holy names, all living beings can become purified and attain all auspiciousness. Nevertheless, for the benefit of ordinary people, I shall tell You about this great vow. O Lord Rama! The Ekadashi of the waxing moon in the month of April/May is known as Mohini Ekadashi. This Ekadashi is most auspicious. By observing this Ekadashi, all reactions to sinful activities, material suffering, and every kind of illusion are destroyed. Now please listen attentively, for I shall narrate the history of this most auspicious Ekadashi.\n\nOnce, on the bank of the sacred Sarasvati River, stood a beautiful city called Bhadravati. That city was ruled by a king named Dyutimana. O Lord Rama! This king was born in the lunar dynasty. He was tolerant and truthful. In the city lived a pious devotee of Lord Vishnu named Dhanapala. By occupation he was a vaishya, a merchant. For the benefit of ordinary people, this devotee Dhanapala built many dharmashalas, schools, temples of Lord Vishnu, hospitals, broad roads, and marketplaces. He also distributed food to the people, dug wells and ponds, and planted flower and fruit gardens. Thus he used his wealth for the welfare of all and thereby justified his name.\n\nThis pious devotee of Lord Vishnu, who was always peaceful, a benefactor of others, and engaged in devotional service to Vishnu, had five sons named Samana, Dyutimana, Medhavi, Sukriti, and Dhrishtabuddhi.\n\nDhrishtabuddhi was the most sinful of these brothers. He was a degraded man, kept company with scoundrels like himself, and was fond of prostitutes, gambling, and wine. He enjoyed killing and tormenting other living beings. Thus he committed every kind of sin and soon became the contemptible son of a most pious father and a disgrace to his family. He never showed respect to the demigods, guests, forefathers, or brahmanas. He constantly thought of how to commit sinful acts. The sinful and degraded Dhrishtabuddhi squandered his father’s wealth on various whims. He ate forbidden foods and constantly drank wine.\n\nOne day, seeing his shameless son walking in a public place with his arm around the shoulder of a prostitute, Dhanapala became desperate. That very day he drove his corrupt son out of the house. Dhrishtabuddhi lost the goodwill of everyone around him, including his father, mother, brothers, other relatives, and friends. Soon he lost his caste and became an object of universal contempt.\n\nHaving been cast into the street, Dhrishtabuddhi continued committing sins with the money he obtained by selling his clothes and ornaments. Soon even this came to an end. He had to go hungry and became emaciated. Now that Dhrishtabuddhi had become a homeless wanderer, his so-called friends and companions turned away from him. His anxiety increased. He had neither food nor clothing and was tormented by hunger. He began to think: ‘What shall I do now? Where shall I go? How shall I survive?’\n\nAfter reflecting, he concluded that his only way out was theft. In search of plunder he began wandering through the city. Several times the king’s guards arrested him but released him, remembering his father’s virtues. Eventually he was arrested for a very serious theft. This time he was brought before the king, who imposed a severe punishment. The king said: ‘O sinful, foolish creature, you no longer have the right to remain in this kingdom, for you are a great sinner. I shall release you now, but please leave my kingdom immediately and go wherever you wish.’\n\nFearing that the next time he would receive an even more severe sentence, Dhrishtabuddhi left the kingdom. He traveled a great distance and reached a remote forest. In the forest he became so weak from hunger and thirst that he began killing animals and birds and eating their raw flesh. With bow and arrows in hand, he wandered through the forest, continuing to kill innocent animals. Thus Dhrishtabuddhi lived in the dark forest for several years, committing sins.\n\nDhrishtabuddhi always suffered and was filled with anxiety, but one day—apparently by the influence of pious deeds from his past—he came to the sacred ashrama of the great sage and ascetic Kaundinya. It was the month of Vaishakha, April/May, and the great sage Kaundinya was returning home after bathing in the Ganges. At that time, by the arrangement of providence, the grief-stricken Dhrishtabuddhi accidentally touched a drop of water that fell from the sage’s garment. By this, Dhrishtabuddhi was immediately freed from the reactions to his sinful activities.\n\nWith folded palms and great humility, he said to the sage Kaundinya: ‘O great brahmana, I am the worst of sinners. There is no sin I have not committed. Now, please tell me of the supreme atonement that even the lowest person like me can easily perform. As a result of committing innumerable sins, I have lost my home, wealth, relatives, and friends. I constantly suffer mental agony.’\n\nHaving heard Dhrishtabuddhi, the great sage Kaundinya, who felt sorrow upon seeing the suffering of others, said: ‘I shall tell you of a noble method by which you can easily and very quickly become free from the reactions to your sins. Please listen attentively.\n\nMohini Ekadashi, which falls during the waxing moon in the month of April/May, completely destroys the reactions to sins as great as Mount Sumeru and committed over many births. Therefore, you should faithfully observe this Ekadashi.’\n\nHearing these words of the great sage, Dhrishtabuddhi rejoiced and observed Ekadashi according to the sage’s rules and regulations. O best of kings! By observing this Mohini Ekadashi, the exceedingly sinful Dhrishtabuddhi soon became free from the reactions to his sins and, obtaining a divine body, returned to the all-auspicious abode of Lord Vishnu upon the back of Garuda. O Ramachandra! This vow destroys all kinds of illusion and the darkness of ignorance. Any merit gained by bathing in sacred waters, giving charity, or performing sacrifices cannot compare with the piety attained by observing this Mohini Ekadashi.’”"
      }
