        "story": "Purifies consciousness and brings auspiciousness and upliftment.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, May 13, 2026\n\nApara Ekadashi, which falls during the waning moon in the month of May/June, is described in the Brahmanda Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nOnce Maharaja Yudhishthira asked Lord Krishna: “O Lord Krishna, O Janardana, what is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of May/June, and what are its glories? Please tell me about it.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O Maharaja Yudhishthira, you have asked Me an intelligent question that brings benefit to everyone. The name of this Ekadashi is Apara. O king! This Ekadashi bestows great merit upon those who observe it and destroys all sinful reactions. By observing this Ekadashi, the reactions to many sinful activities are nullified, such as killing a brahmana, killing a cow, killing an embryo through abortion, criticizing others, illicit sexual relations, lying, giving false testimony, boasting, reciting the Vedas or teaching them for money, and falsifying the sacred scriptures.\n\nA cheat, a false astrologer, and a fraudulent physician—such people are as sinful as a false witness. All such sinfulness is nullified by observing this Apara Ekadashi. Any kshatriya who abandons his duty and flees from the battlefield certainly goes to hell. If such a person observes this Ekadashi with faith, he too attains heaven.”\n\nLord Krishna continued: “O king! A disciple who, after receiving knowledge from his spiritual master, reviles him falls into great sin. Such a condemned sinner can become free from the reaction to this sin by observing Apara Ekadashi and thus attain the supreme goal of life. O king of kings! The result attained by bathing three times at Pushkara in the month of Kartika; the merit acquired by bathing at Prayaga in January when the sun enters the constellation of Capricorn; the results attained by observing the vow of Shivaratri in Kashi and worshiping the lotus feet of Vishnu in Gaya; the auspicious fruits of bathing in the Gautami River when Jupiter enters the constellation of Leo; and the fruits attained by visiting Kedarnatha during the Kumbha Mela, by visiting and worshiping at Badrinatha, by bathing at Kurukshetra during a solar eclipse, and by giving elephants, cows, gold, and land in charity—all these are easily attained by observing the vow of Apara Ekadashi.\n\nThis Ekadashi is like a sharp axe that cuts down the tree of sin and like a forest fire that burns all sins to ashes. It is like the radiant sun that dispels the darkness of sin and like a lion that devours the deer of sin in the forest of sins. O king! By observing this Apara Ekadashi and worshiping Lord Vishnu in His form as Trivikrama, a person attains the all-auspicious abode of Lord Vishnu. Anyone who hears or reads the glories of this Ekadashi becomes free from the reactions to all his sins. For the benefit of everyone, I have narrated these glories to you.”"
