      "en": {
        "name": "Nirjala Ekadashi",
        "description": "Benefits: Grants the combined fruits of observing all other Ekadashis of the year. Story: This strict fast is observed without water and is known as the most austere Ekadashi.",
        "benefits": "Grants the combined fruits of observing all other Ekadashis of the year.",
        "story": "This strict fast is observed without water and is known as the most austere Ekadashi.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, June 25, 2026\n\nThe description of Pandava Nirjala Ekadashi, which falls in the month of May/June, is found in the Brahma Vaivarta Purana in a conversation between Vyasadeva and Bhimasena.\n\nOnce Bhimasena, the younger brother of Yudhishthira, addressed the great sage Srila Vyasadeva: “O most learned and worshipable grandfather, please hear my request. My elder brother Yudhishthira, my mother Kuntidevi, my brothers Arjuna, Nakula, and Sahadeva, and Draupadi eat nothing on Ekadashi day. They, especially Yudhishthira, constantly tell me that I should fast on Ekadashi. But I always reply that I am unable to fast, although I know that fasting on Ekadashi is prescribed in the scriptures. Yet I cannot tolerate hunger and therefore cannot fast. I can give charity according to my means; I can worship Lord Keshava according to the rules and regulations, but I cannot fast. Therefore, please instruct me: how can I obtain the results of observing Ekadashi without fasting?”\n\nHearing these words of Bhimasena, Sri Vyasadeva said: “O Bhima! If you wish to attain heaven and avoid hell, then you must refrain from eating on the Ekadashi days of every month.”\n\nBhima said: “O great sage! I am unable to fast on the twenty-four Ekadashis each year as prescribed by the Lord. What to speak of fasting day and night—I cannot tolerate hunger for even a single moment. The fire of hunger known as vrika always burns in my stomach, and it can be extinguished only by abundant food. Gathering all my strength, I can fast for one day in a year. Therefore, please instruct me and tell me of a vow by following which I may attain benefit both in this life and in the next.”\n\nSri Vyasadeva replied: “O king! You have already heard from me about the Vedic religious principles and the duties of human beings. But in this age of Kali, no one is capable of following all these rules and restrictions. Therefore, I shall tell you of an exalted method by which you can attain wonderful results. This method is the essence of all the Puranas. Anyone who fasts on the Ekadashis of both the waxing and waning moons never goes to hell.”\n\nHearing Vyasadeva’s words, the mighty warrior Bhimasena became frightened and trembled like a banyan leaf. He said: “O grandfather! In that case, what shall I do? I am completely unable to fast twice a month throughout the whole year. Therefore, my lord, please instruct me how to observe a vow that bestows the greatest merit and all kinds of auspicious benefit.”\n\nSri Vyasadeva replied: “The Ekadashi that falls during the waxing moon in the month of May/June, when the sun is in either Taurus or Gemini, is called Nirjala Ekadashi. On this Ekadashi one must observe a complete fast, without even a drop of water. On this day one may perform achamana for purification by drinking an amount of water in which a mustard seed or a drop of gold could be immersed. The aforementioned quantity of water should be placed in the palm, formed so as to resemble a cow’s ear. If one drinks more or less than the specified amount, it is considered the same as drinking wine. One must not eat on this Ekadashi, otherwise the vow is broken. One must not even drink water from sunrise on Ekadashi until sunrise on Dvadashi. If one strictly observes this Ekadashi without water, one can attain the results of observing all the Ekadashis of the year. Early in the morning on Dvadashi, one should bathe and give gold and water in charity to the brahmanas. Thereafter one should happily eat together with the brahmanas.\n\nO Bhimasena! Now please hear of the merits a person acquires by observing this Ekadashi. By following this Ekadashi, one can obtain the results of observing all the Ekadashis throughout the year.\n\nOnce Lord Vishnu, who holds the conch, disc, plough, and lotus flower, told me that if a person abandons various separate obligations, surrenders himself unto Him, and observes this Nirjala Ekadashi, which is very dear to Him, then he certainly becomes free from the consequences of all sinful activities. In this Kali-yuga, it is impossible to attain the supreme goal through charity or by following the rules of the smriti scriptures. Indeed, the religious principles of the Vedas are not effective in this age, which is contaminated by numerous faults.\n\nO son of Vayu! What more shall I tell you? Eating is forbidden on every Ekadashi, and even water is forbidden on Nirjala Ekadashi. By observing this Ekadashi, a person obtains the results of visiting all holy places. At the time of death, such a person does not encounter the frightening Yamadutas; rather, he is met by the divine Vishnudutas, who carry him to the abode of Vishnu. If, after observing this Ekadashi, a person gives water and cows in charity, he becomes free from all sins.”\n\nWhen the other Pandavas heard the glories of this Ekadashi, they too decided to observe it. From that day onward, this Ekadashi became known as Pandava Ekadashi or Bhima Ekadashi. If a person observes this Ekadashi, his sins, equal in magnitude to Mount Sumeru or Mount Mandara, are immediately burned to ashes. O king! Lord Krishna has declared that any pious activity—such as bathing in a sacred place, giving charity, reciting Vedic mantras, or performing sacrifices—when performed on this Ekadashi day yields extraordinary results. One who reads or hears narrations of the glories of this Ekadashi with devotion returns to the abode of Vaikuntha. Simply by hearing the glories of this Ekadashi, one attains the results of observing the Amavasya vow together with Pratipada and making ritual offerings to the forefathers during a solar eclipse.”"
      }
