      "en": {
        "name": "Pavitropana Ekadashi",
        "description": "Benefits: Blesses one with righteous children, purifies the family line, and brings welfare. Story: Helps remove past-life curses and obtain pious offspring.",
        "benefits": "Blesses one with righteous children, purifies the family line, and brings welfare.",
        "story": "Helps remove past-life curses and obtain pious offspring.",
        "full_description": "Ekadashi, August 23, 2026\n\nThe glories of Pavitropana Ekadashi are described in the Bhavishyottara Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nOnce Maharaja Yudhishthira addressed Krishna with these words: “O Madhusudana, killer of the demon Madhu! What is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waxing moon in the month of July/August, and what are its glories? Please tell me about this in detail.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O king! This sacred Ekadashi is called Pavitra Ekadashi. Now, please attentively hear the narration of this Ekadashi, which destroys the reactions to all sins. By hearing the glories of this Ekadashi, one attains the results of the Vajapeya sacrifice.\n\nIn ancient times, at the beginning of Dvapara-yuga, there lived a king named Mahijit, who ruled a kingdom called Mahishmatipuri. Because the king had no sons, he found no joy in either affairs of state or amusements. A married man who has no son experiences not the slightest happiness either in this life or in the next. For many years the king unsuccessfully tried to become the father of a son, but he was not fortunate enough to obtain such a jewel-like son, the source of all joy.\n\nRealizing the pitiable circumstances in which he found himself, one day the king summoned his subjects, whom he regarded as his own children, to the royal assembly and said to them: “O dear subjects, I have never committed sinful acts in my life; I have not filled my treasury with wealth acquired by unrighteous means; I have not taken the wealth of brahmanas or demigods. On the contrary, I conquered this world by following the code of honor, I cared for you as my own children, I always punished even those close to me, such as my brother and relatives, without hesitation, judging them according to their deeds, and I showed proper respect even to an enemy if he was noble and pious. O brahmanas, although I have followed such a religious path, why am I deprived of a son? Please reflect upon the reasons for this and advise me.”\n\nAfter hearing the sorrowful words of King Mahijit, the king’s brahmana counselors conferred and decided that, for the king’s benefit, they would go to the forest and visit the ashramas of great sages who knew the past, present, and future. And so they did. They entered the forest and began visiting the ashramas of great sages scattered throughout it.\n\nAt last they met Lomasa Muni, who was performing severe austerities. His body was spiritual and full of bliss. He observed strict fasting, controlled his senses, knew the science of the Eternal Principles of Religion, was learned in all the scriptures, and his lifespan equaled that of Brahma. Whenever one kalpa of Brahma came to an end, one hair, or loma, fell from his body, and therefore the sage was called Lomasa. The sage Lomasa knew the past, present, and future.\n\nThe king’s counselors offered obeisances to the sage and humbly said: “O great sage! By our great good fortune we have met a great soul like you.” The sage Lomasa asked: “Who are you? Why have you come here? Why do you praise me?” The brahmanas replied: “O great sage! We have come to you to dispel our doubts. O lord! Our king has no sons. We are his subjects, and the king treats us as his own children. We are sorrowful to see our lord’s grief. O best of brahmanas, we wish to perform severe austerities here. By our king’s great good fortune, today we have met a great personality like you. The darshan of a great personality enables one to attain every perfection. Please give us instructions by following which our childless king may obtain a son.”\n\nHearing these sincere prayers, the sage Lomasa entered deep meditation for a moment and immediately saw the previous life of King Mahijit. He then said that in his previous birth the king had been a poor vaishya, a merchant. He had committed sinful acts. Once, while traveling from village to village and trading, he became thirsty. It was noon on Dvadashi in the month of July. Soon he found a beautiful lake and decided to drink from it. At that time a cow with her calf came to the shore of the lake to drink. As soon as the cow tried to do so, the merchant immediately drove her away and drank first himself. In this way the merchant committed a sin. Later, by virtue of his merits, the merchant was born as King Mahijit, but he had no son.\n\nHearing these words of the great sage, the king’s counselors said: “O great sage! The Puranas state that pious merit destroys the reactions to sinful activities. Therefore, please give us instructions by which all the reactions to the king’s sins will be destroyed and he will be able to become the father of a son.”\n\nThe great sage Lomasa replied: “There is a famous and auspicious Ekadashi known as Pavitra Ekadashi, which falls during the waxing moon in the month of July/August. All of you and the king should properly observe this Ekadashi. If you follow my advice, the king will certainly be blessed with a son.”\n\nHearing these words of the sage Lomasa, all the king’s counselors immediately became happy and satisfied. They bowed to the sage and returned home. Then they met King Mahijit and told him in detail everything they had heard from the great sage Lomasa. Later, when the proper time arrived, the king’s counselors remembered the sage’s advice and, together with the king, properly observed the vow of Pavitra Ekadashi. On Dvadashi day, as the sage had advised, the counselors transferred all the accumulated merit to the king. By the influence of this merit, the queen became pregnant and, in due course, gave birth to a beautiful son.\n\nO King Yudhishthira, anyone who observes this sacred Ekadashi becomes free from the reactions to sinful activities and becomes happy both in this life and in the next. Anyone who hears the glories of this Ekadashi attains the happiness arising from fatherhood in this life and returns to God in the next life.”"
      }
