        "full_description": "Ekadashi, September 7, 2026\n\nThe glories of Annada, or Aja, Ekadashi are described in the Brahma Vaivarta Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nMaharaja Yudhishthira said: “O Krishna! What is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of August/September? Please be kind and tell me about it.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O king! Hear Me with full attention. The name of this auspicious Ekadashi, which removes all sins, is Annada Ekadashi. One who observes this Ekadashi and worships Lord Hrishikesha, the master of the senses, becomes free from the reactions to his sinful activities.\n\nIn ancient times there lived an emperor named Harishchandra. He was a most truthful and honest man. It so happened that he desired to keep his word, and because of this the king lost his kingdom. He was even forced to sell himself, his wife, and his son into servitude. O king! This pious emperor became the servant of a dog-eater. Nevertheless, he continued to adhere unwaveringly to his principles of life.\n\nBy the order of his master, the dog-eater, he began removing clothes from dead bodies at cremation grounds and accepting them as wages. Despite such a pitiable condition, he continued to remain virtuous and truthful. Many years passed in this way. Then one day the king, feeling miserable, began to reflect: “What shall I do? Where shall I go? How shall I attain deliverance?”\n\nUnderstanding that the king was experiencing great sorrow, the sage Gautama came to him. On seeing the great sage, the king thought that Lord Brahma, the creator, had created the brahmanas for the welfare of other people. Then the king offered respectful obeisances to the best of brahmanas and stood before him with folded hands. He told the sage the sorrowful story of his life.\n\nAfter hearing the king, the great sage Gautama was greatly astonished and gave the king the following instructions: “O king! Annada Ekadashi, which falls during the waning moon in the month of August/September, is supremely auspicious and removes all sins. Your good fortune is that this Ekadashi is approaching. You should observe this Ekadashi by fasting and remaining awake throughout the night. As a result, all the reactions to your sinful activities will soon be destroyed. O best of kings, it is only by your influence that I have come here.” Having instructed King Harishchandra, the great sage Gautama disappeared. Thereafter, according to the sage’s instructions, the king observed the vow of Annada Ekadashi and became free from all sinful reactions.\n\nLord Krishna concluded: “O lion-like king! The wonderful influence of this Ekadashi is such that by its power a person is immediately freed from the suffering he was destined to endure for many, many years. By the influence of this Ekadashi, King Harishchandra regained his wife, and his dead son returned to life. Rejoicing, the demigods began to beat drums, and a shower of flowers fell from the sky. Thereafter, again by the influence of this Ekadashi, the king enjoyed his sovereignty without obstruction. In the end, the king went to the spiritual world together with his relatives, associates, and subjects.\n\nO king! Anyone who observes this Ekadashi becomes free from sins and goes to the spiritual world. By hearing and reading the glories of this Ekadashi, one attains the results of a horse sacrifice.”"
