        "full_description": "Ekadashi, October 6, 2026\n\nThe glories of Indira Ekadashi are described in the Brahma Vaivarta Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nMaharaja Yudhishthira said: “O Krishna! O Madhusudana! O killer of the demon Madhu! What is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waning moon in the month of September/October? What are the rules and restrictions for observing this Ekadashi, and what merit can be acquired by observing it?”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “This sacred Ekadashi is called Indira Ekadashi. By observing this Ekadashi, one can deliver one’s fallen ancestors from hell and become free from the reactions to all sinful activities. O king!\n\nOnce there lived a ruler named Indrasena. He lived in Satya-yuga and was skilled in subduing his enemies. He ruled his kingdom of Mahishmatipuri, which prospered in every respect. He was surrounded by children and grandchildren, and everyone lived happily.\n\nThe king was attached to devotional service to Vishnu. Being a devotee absorbed in spiritual knowledge, he spent his time chanting the holy names of Sri Govinda, the bestower of liberation. One day, while the king was seated upon his throne, Sri Narada Muni unexpectedly appeared before him, descending from heaven. Seeing the great sage Narada, the king immediately rose and offered him respectful obeisances. Thereafter the king properly worshiped the sage, offering him sixteen ingredients. Seated comfortably, the sage asked Indrasena: “O great king! Are your subjects happy and prosperous? Is your mind fixed in religious principles? Are you rendering devotional service to Vishnu?”\n\nThe king replied: “O best of sages! By your mercy, everything in the kingdom is well and auspicious. Today my life has become successful by your darshan, and my sacrifices have borne fruit. O sage among the demigods! Please tell me the reason for your visit.”\n\nHearing these humble words of the king, Narada Muni said: “O lion-like king! Hear of a wondrous event that happened to me. O best of kings!\n\nOnce I traveled from the abode of Lord Brahma to the abode of Yamaraja. When I reached his kingdom, Yamaraja respectfully welcomed me and properly worshiped me. After I had been comfortably seated, I offered prayers to the pious and truthful Yamaraja. In Yamaraja’s assembly I saw your father, endowed with great piety. Because he had broken a vow, your father was forced to remain there. O king! He gave me a message for you.\n\nHe said: ‘Indrasena, the king of Mahishmatipuri, is my son. O lord, please tell him that because of certain sinful activities committed in a previous life, I now reside in the abode of Yamaraja. Therefore, he should observe the vow of Indira Ekadashi and offer the merit to me. Then I shall be freed from my present circumstances.’\n\nNarada Muni continued: “O king! This is your father’s request to you. Therefore, in order to help your father attain the spiritual world, you should observe the vow of Indira Ekadashi.”\n\nThen King Indrasena said: “O sage among the demigods, now kindly explain to me the procedure for observing this Indira Ekadashi.”\n\nNarada Muni replied: “On the day before Ekadashi, one should rise early in the morning, bathe, and make a ritual offering to the ancestors for their satisfaction. On that day one should eat only once and sleep on the floor at night. On Ekadashi day one should rise at dawn, brush one’s teeth, wash one’s hands, and bathe. Thereafter one should vow not to engage in any material enjoyment and thus observe a complete fast. In addition, one should pray to the Lord with these words: ‘O lotus-eyed Lord, I take shelter in You.’”"
