        "full_description": "Ekadashi, October 22, 2026\n\nThe glories of Pasankusha Ekadashi, which falls during the waxing moon in the month of September/October, are described in the Brahma Vaivarta Purana in a conversation between Lord Krishna and Maharaja Yudhishthira.\n\nMaharaja Yudhishthira asked: “O Madhusudana, what is the name of the Ekadashi that falls during the waxing moon in the month of September/October? Please be kind and tell me about it.”\n\nLord Krishna replied: “O best of kings! This Ekadashi is called Pasankusha Ekadashi. Now, please hear about this Ekadashi, which destroys all sins. Some people call this Ekadashi Papankusha Ekadashi. On this Ekadashi day one should worship Lord Padmanabha. This Ekadashi bestows heavenly enjoyment, liberation, and everything desired upon those who observe it. By chanting the holy names of Lord Vishnu, one can acquire the merit of visiting all the holy places on earth. If a conditioned soul, instead of committing various sins, takes shelter of Lord Hari, who is expert in delivering fallen souls, and offers obeisances unto Him, that soul does not go to hell.\n\nVaishnavas who criticize Lord Shiva and Shaivas who criticize Lord Vishnu undoubtedly go to hell. The result attained by performing one thousand horse sacrifices or one hundred Rajasuya sacrifices cannot equal even one-sixteenth of the merit attained by observing this Ekadashi.\n\nThere is no merit in this world equal to the merit of observing Ekadashi. Therefore, no other day is as sacred as this Ekadashi day, which is very dear to Lord Padmanabha. O king! As soon as a person becomes unable to observe Ekadashi, sins begin to dwell within his body. This Ekadashi bestows heavenly enjoyment, liberation, freedom from disease, beautiful women, and grain upon its followers. O protector of the earth! If a person observes this Ekadashi and remains awake throughout the night of Ekadashi, he easily attains the abode of Lord Vishnu.”\n\nLord Krishna continued: “O best of kings! By observing the vow of this Ekadashi, one can save ten generations of ancestors on the mother’s side, ten generations on the father’s side, and ten generations on the wife’s side. If a person observes this Ekadashi in childhood, youth, or old age, he does not encounter the sufferings of material existence. A person who strictly observes this Pasankusha or Papankusha Ekadashi becomes free from the reactions to all his sinful activities and, at the end of life, returns to the abode of Lord Vishnu.\n\nIf a person gives gold, sesame seeds, land, cows, grain, water, canopies, or footwear in charity, then at the end of life he returns to the abode of Lord Vishnu. Anyone who spends his days without performing pious activities is like a dead man, although he breathes. O best of kings! A person who digs wells and lakes for the benefit of others, gives land and buildings in charity, and performs other pious activities, such as arranging sacrifices, does not become an object of Yamaraja’s punishment. Only by piety do people live long, become wealthy, take birth in aristocratic families, and become free from disease. The meaning is that the direct result of observing Ekadashi is the attainment of devotional service to Krishna, while the indirect result is the attainment of temporary material benefits.”"
